    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to lace made at Chantilly, Oise departement, France, since the 18th century. It is characterized by being delicate, made of silk or linen, and having a six-sided mesh ground and a distinctive floral or scrolled design. Later designs include ribbons, naturalistic flowers, and other designs on a dotted background. Chantilly lace dating from the 19th century was produced in three colors: white, black, and "blond," which was the natural beige color of silk.  It was made into large items such as veils, shawls, other of apparel, and household dresser covers and draperies. Chantilly lace was copied in machine lace from 1840 on.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
